Commentary.Commentary: Back with the action! The Indian fielders have spread out on the field. Rory Burns and Haseeb Hameed will open the innings for England. Ishant Sharma will begin with the ball. Here he comes...

Right. The ball is in the court of the English batters now, as their bowlers have delivered the goods. Apart from Root, their batters have been tame and will look to make amends. Will they be able to do so? Or will the Indian bowlers save their blushes? Join us for England's reply shortly.

A dramatic turn-around for India, as after the highs of Lord's, they have been pulled down to the ground. Their batting line-up could only muster 78 and they will be very disappointed with the same. Apart from Rohit Sharma, none of the other batters showed any fight. Rahane looked nervy but forged a good stand with Rohit, but when that was broken, there was a procession of wickets and India have folded for a very low score. Apart from these two, none of the other batters even crossed the double-digit mark. A batting display to forget, really.

What a sublime bowling display this has been by England. Their bowling looked thin on paper before the game got underway, but their bowlers have delivered the goods and have bundled this Indian side out for just 78! The ball was set rolling by James Anderson as in no time, he took 3 wickets in the first hour in the first session and India never recovered from the same. Robinson got a wicket towards the end of Lunch and once they came out, post the first session, they were on a mission. Pant fell quickly and once Rohit Sharma was sent packing, India fell from 67/5 to being bundled out for 78. Overton finished with 3 whereas, Robinson and Curran ended with two to their name. Brilliant stuff!

OUT! CAUGHT! There it is! What a comeback this has been from the English bowlers. Overton serves a good-length ball, down leg, Siraj makes room on the off side. Siraj looks to cut this one over the slip cordon but he fails to get any elevation and the ball goes towards Joe Root at first slip who jumps to take a good catch. INDIA HAVE BEEN BOWLED OUT FOR 78!
Commentary.Howout: c Joe Root b Craig Overton

Curran appeals and runs away in celebration as the umpire raises his finger. Bumrah takes the review but it does not work out as UltraEdge shows no bat and Ball Tracker shows three reds. One more wicket away are the Brits. Sam Curran is on a hat-trick too!

OUT! LBW! Another one bites the dust and India are falling apart here. Wonderfully bowled by Curran and the only recognized batter has been sent packing. Sam Curran digs in a yorker this time, taking Jadeja by surprise. Jadeja gets his bat down late and misses as the ball takes the pad and goes to the keeper. A loud appeal and the umpire raises his finger. India have all three of their reviews left and so, Jadeja takes the review. No bat shows the UltraEdge. Ball Tracker shows THREE REDS. The on-field decision stays on and England just need 2 more wickets to bundle India!
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Sam Curran

OUT! EDGED AND TAKEN! Overton gets back-to-back wickets and England are on fire here. The hero of the Lord's Test, Shami, has to walk back for a golden duck. 67/7 - a depressing scoreline if you are supporting India. Back of a length this time, around off, Mohammed Shami hops and looks to defend, but only gets an outside edge. The ball goes to the right of third slip, where Rory Burns moves that side and pouches this. Craig Overton is on a hat-trick here!
Commentary.Howout: c Rory Burns b Craig Overton

Commentary.Commentary: Mohammed Shami is the new man in.

OUT! CAUGHT! Oh, dear! The same story continues for Rohit Sharma. He looks to play the pull shot, but he gives an easy catch to the silly mid on fielder. He has played 105 balls, but he has put all of that down the drain as he gifts his wicket away. Craig Overton runs in and hurls a short delivery, around off, the ball does not come onto the bat nicely as Rohit Sharma looks set to play the pull shot. He miscues it and the ball takes the lower half of the blade and lobs towards Ollie Robinson at silly mid on, who will take this in his sleep. So, obviously, he does the same while he is awake. India slip further as they lose their sixth wicket!
Commentary.Howout: c Ollie Robinson b Craig Overton

Pant has struggled to get into a good rhythm in this series so far and the same story continues. Back-of-a-length ball, angling away outside off. Rishabh Pant could have left it alone, but he decides to poke at this and gets an outside edge towards Jos Buttler, who takes his 5th catch of the innings. Ollie Robinson is delighted and England will look to get these remaining wickets quickly as India have a long tail.
Commentary.Howout: c Jos Buttler b Ollie Robinson

The English players are in a huddle near the ropes. Joe Root has a quick word and they disperse to their respective positions on the field. Rohit Sharma is joined by the attack-minded, Rishabh Pant out in the middle. Ollie Robinson will complete his over now...
... Day 1, Session 2 ...

Not at all what the Indians would have been looking for after their exploits in the second Test. Their openers have usually set the platform for them in this series, but in this game, the opening duo was broken on ball 5 of the Test match. Pujara continued to struggle as he went back for just 1 run. The skipper, Kohli, who has been searching for his 71st ton for a while now, has to wait a bit longer, as he was snaked by a beauty from Jimmy. Rohit Sharma has looked the most settled of all the batters and he has been well supported by Rahane since the 3 wickets have fallen, but the Indian deputy was sent packing right towards the end of the session. Rohit Sharma will look to bat well and take India to safer shores. It should be an interesting session post Lunch. Join us for the same at 1.40 pm local (12.40 pm GMT).

What a first session it has been for the English Lions! They have pushed the demons of the last game out of their systems and have come out all guns blazing and will be very happy with their work so far. It has been all about James Anderson as the veteran has run through the top-order of the Indians. Jos Buttler has been his partner in crime as he has taken four catches as well. Jimmy removed Rahul in the very first over and Pujara was soon sent back. He kept probing and also removed his nemesis, Kohli soon after. Robinson has been decent and got a wicket right at the stroke of Lunch. Curran has been slightly wayward and Overton has been impressive in his short spell. Overall, the Brits have asked the right questions and are on top after the first session.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Ollie Robinson has struck for England in the last over before Lunch and India are in deep trouble now. Good-length ball, around the fifth stump channel. Ajinkya Rahane hangs his bat at it and gets an outside edge towards Jos Buttler behind the sticks, who pouches it comfortably. Ollie Robinson gets rid of India's vice-captain, just when he was looking to steady the innings with his batting partner. England are bossing this game now and they will be a happier team going into Lunch on Day 1. With that, IT IS LUNCH ON DAY 1!
Commentary.Howout: c Jos Buttler b Ollie Robinson

DRINKS BREAK. What a first hour of play this has been for England. They needed to start strongly after the last Test and they have done that supremely well. It has all been about James Anderson as he has run riot through the Indian top-order, removing Rahul, Pujara, and skipper, Kohli. Only Rohit Sharma has looked settled for India and along with Rahane, they will look to weather the storm and reach Lunch unscathed.

In another episode of the Jimmy vs VK show, it is the English veteran who has come out on top again. Length ball, around the fifth stump channel. Virat Kohli plays a very loose-looking shot, as he looks to drive through covers but the ball nips away slightly, and he only manages an outside edge and Jos Buttler behind the sticks does the rest. Anderson is pumped up and India are three down inside the first hour of play and they are in some trouble now.
Commentary.Howout: c Jos Buttler b James Anderson

OUT! EDGED AND TAKEN! What a start this is for Anderson and England. They have struck again and India's wall, Pujara, has been breached. Anderson probes with his line and length and makes Pujara play at this, which proves to be his undoing. Again, he dishes a couple of inswingers and poses a question on Pujara's mind, then, he serves an outswinger in the zone of uncertainty and gets the better of Pujara. On a length this time, around the off pole, the ball hits the deck and nips away beautifully. Cheteshwar Pujara pokes his blade at this, looking to defend, but the ball catches the outside edge, due to the away movement. Jos Buttler dives low to his right and pouches this. India have started off poorly and the crowd are loving it!

OUT! EDGED AND TAKEN! This is a great start by England and they have struck in the very first over. This is just what they would have wanted after the Lord's Test. This is well set-up by Jimmy, as in the previous ball, he bowled a ball in the channel outside off, which nipped back in significantly and hence, Rahul went to play at this, keeping in mind the inswing. Usually, when there is a delivery in such a channel, KL has been wary and has left it, but this time, he goes chasing after this and pays the price, as this delivery nipped away late and caught the edge. James Anderson runs in and serves a fuller ball, in the fourth stump channel, gets it to move away as well. KL Rahul looks for the big, booming drive through the off side, but only manages an outside edge, which is easily gulped down by Jos Buttler behind the sticks. The crowd is loving it and India's opening stand does not last the first over!
Commentary.Howout: c Jos Buttler b James Anderson

All set for the action to begin here. The English players have spread out on the field here. Rohit Sharma and KL Rahul will open the innings for India. James Anderson to speed-in first up with the new ball in hand. Here he comes...
Right. Time for the National Anthems now. First, it will be India's 'Jana Gana Mana', followed by England's 'God Save The Queen'.

England (Playing XI) - Rory Burns, Haseeb Hameed, Dawid Malan (In for Dom Sibley), Joe Root (C), Jonny Bairstow, Jos Buttler (WK), Moeen Ali, Sam Curran, Craig Overton (In for Mark Wood), Ollie Robinson, James Anderson.
India (Unchanged XI) - Rohit Sharma, KL Rahul, Cheteshwar Pujara, Virat Kohli (C), Ajinkya Rahane, Rishabh Pant (WK), Ravindra Jadeja, Mohammed Shami, Ishant Sharma, Jasprit Bumrah, Mohammed Siraj.

The England captain, Joe Root, says that they are not too disappointed to be bowling and in recent history, the ground keeps getting better and better as they go on. Informs that they have two changes as Dawid Malan and Craig Overton come in and Dom Sibley and Mark Wood miss out. Says that the choice of playing Overton over Mahmood was made on the conditions out in the middle and Mahmood is playing very well, but Overton has consistently performed in county conditions. On the opening combination of Burns and Hameed, Root says that they have a huge amount of confidence in them and it takes a lot of character to play at the top of the order.

Virat Kohli, the Indian captain, says that it is a surprise as he has won the toss. Adds that this pitch looks a bit different and there is very little grass. About changing the playing XI, says that they thought about adding Ashwin in the side but the extra seamer is valuable in these conditions. Says that it is up to the boys to take up this winning culture and the boys have been brilliant so far. Adds that Ravindra Jadeja will have a much bigger role in this match for sure. Credits the openers KL Rahul and Rohit Sharma for the foundation they have been laying upfront. Speaking about his own form, he says that he has been working hard in the nets and looks to contribute to the team without thinking about how many runs he gets.
TOSS - All in readiness for the flip of the coin at Leeds. Virat Kohli and Joe Root are out there, in their blazers. It is Root who spins the coin and Kohli wins the toss. INDIA HAVE ELECTED TO BAT!

England look like a shadow of their former selves as they have struggled to gain momentum and have not shown impetus to battle this hot-headed Indian side. They have a lot of issues and things are looking bleak at the moment for them. With their batting, Joe Root is the only one who has shown any skill and fight, while the other batters have just not been able to stand up and share the responsibility with their skipper. Dom Sibley and Zak Crawley have been dropped and Dawid Malan has been recalled and will be looking to make an impact. In their bowling department, they have been dealt another blow as Mark Wood has been ruled out of this game. As they do not have Stuart Broad as well, their bowling attack looks slightly thin. It will be interesting to see what changes the English Lions decide to make.

The confidence is definitely with the visitors as in the last game, they rose to the challenge at the Home of Cricket and dismantled England. All departments of the Indian vehicle seem to be working in tandem and they are looking very good, heading into this game. Their openers have fired, the middle order showed fight, the tail wagged for longer than what anybody would have expected, their pacers have bowled with fire and zest. Do not expect them to make any changes as such, but Shardul Thakur has been proclaimed fit and it will be interesting to see if he makes his way back into the team. All eyes will also be on Ravichandran Ashwin and whether Virat Kohli decides to hand his veteran a chance in this game. Everything looks good for them to take a 2-0 lead in this series, but it depends on whether India can continue with their momentum.

Hello folks! After a riveting game of cricket in the second Test at Lord's, wherein India walked the talk and smacked the Brits towards the fag end of Day 5, which resulted in India taking a 1-0 lead in the 5-game Test series, now, we are all braced and ready for the third time that these two giants clash their swords as the third Test at Headingley is upon us. On that note, hello and a very warm welcome to the coverage...
We are set to resume! Rohit Sharma and KL Rahul walk out to the middle. England fielders spread out on the field. James Anderson will start with the ball.

Update 11.25 am Local (10:25 am GMT) - Oops, we might have spoken a bit too soon. It is now drizzling out there and the pitch has been put under the covers. It is not at all heavy so hopefully, it is just a passing shower. The English players are waiting patiently near the ropes. Now, the covers have been taken off too!

It was a tough innings for the Indian bowlers. The pitch was much easier to bat on and they struggled big time. Mohammed Shami was the pick of the bowlers as he took 4 wickets while everyone except Ishant Sharma took 2 wickets. Sharma was not at his best and was quite expensive too. Overall, it was an innings that they would like to forget. It is now time for the batters to get out there and score runs. Their first task would be to cut down the deficit and erase it. Stay tuned as India's second innings begins shortly.

England batted really well. All the batters in the top 4 crossed the 50-run mark and gave them a strong start. But the star player was once again Joe Root as he scored a sublime ton and continued his dominance over the Indian bowlers. The lower order could not get many runs but the tail wagged a bit as Craig Overton got valuable 32 runs to help them cross 400. The lead of 354 is a massive one and the English pacers would be raring to go hard at the Indian batters.

A wonderful batting show by England. India did get the last two wickets very early but overall, it is an innings dominated by England. They have a massive lead on the board and would look to push for a huge victory.

We are set for the action! The Indian players spread out on the field. Craig Overton and Ollie Robinson stride out to the middle. Mohammed Shami to start with the ball.

Update 10:45 am Local (9:45 am GMT) - According to the recent tweet by BCCI, there is a slight drizzle at the moment at Leeds and the pitch is under covers. We hope that we start on time though. But the live visuals now show that the Indian players are dressed up and heading out to the middle. We should probably start on time now.

Dominic Cork is down for the pitch report, he says that the full-length region outside the off stump for the right-handed batters has a bit of rough so that could assist the spinners like Moeen Ali. Adds that there is a bit of mizzle in the air so the pacers might be able to get some help too.

Nasser Hussain (on air) says that he likes how England have changed their batting line-up. Adds that conditions have improved and Day 2 was a great day to bat. Says that for England it was a good toss to lose as the pitch gets better to bat on with time. Hussain says that India has a lot of seam bowlers but England got the ball to swing and that helped them a lot. Further adds that India were smart with their aggression in the second Test and England have tried to do just that in this game. Mentions that it is quite cold here and the English supporters are loving this atmosphere.

It is almost certain that India will get to bat here on Day 3. They had a disastrous outing on Day 1, but their form so far in the series has been quite good. Plus, the pitch has gotten much easier to bat on and that should help them. But England have put on a massive total already and the Indian batters will be under great pressure in the second innings. How players like Rohit Sharma, KL Rahul, Ajinkya Rahane, Virat Kohli and Cheteshwar Pujara bat in the next innings could very well decide which way this game goes.

Hello and a very warm welcome to Day 3 of the third Test between England and India. We have witnessed two days of Test cricket so far and both of them were dominated by England. They now lead by 345 runs and with two wickets in hand, the hosts would look to get as many runs as possible this morning. India, on the other hand, would be desperate to take the last two wickets and put on a big score in their second innings. Stay tuned as we find out what exactly happens.
... Day 3, Session 1 ...

India will now hope they can take the remaining two wickets as quickly as possible. Pretty sure their top order batters will already be thinking about batting. They will be eager to bat here and hope they can make use of the conditions as the wicket here just gets better. England on the other hand, will hope they can add as many as possible, time is not an issue, so they would be happy to bat for as long as possible, 500 will probably be their first aim and they would hope to bat India out of the game. Will Day 3 also be dominated by the hosts or is there going to be comeback from the visitors? Something tells me it is going to be the latter. Do join us for all the action at 1100 local (1000 GMT). Till then, take care and goodbye!

Have to feel sorry for the Indian bowlers, most of them were not that bad, they actually were quite decent but there was not a lot of assistance for them from this wicket. Yes, they were a tad inconsistent with their lengths but overall, they were quite decent with the ball. Except for Ishant, everyone picked a wicket at least, Ishant was quite flat, he was way too straight and leaked runs. Except for him, the rest did a commendable job. They will be quite pleased with the last session or there was a possibility of England heading into Day 3 being just 4 or 5 down.

The day was all about the England's top three and Root because the middle order and the lower order did not do a lot! The damage the top four did is the reason why England are in the position they are in. All the top three scored fifties but none of them went onto make it into a ton but Root did do so as he went on to score yet another century. Also, the English skipper managed to score those runs at a brisk rate. They made the Indian bowlers toil hard in the first two sessions. They went about things slowly in the first, the second they managed to score quicker, they came out in the third session with even more positive intent, they did manage to score at a decent click but lost quite a few wickets. Still, though, they will be pretty pleased with where they are in the game, yes, their position could have been a lot better but they are well and truly in the driver's seat.

End of another day which has belonged to the hosts! They are way, way ahead in the game at the moment despite losing 5 wickets in this session. Yes, they did lose 5 wickets but they have ended up scoring more than 120 runs which has seen that lead grow to over 340.

Every bowler tried hard but didn't get help from the pitch. India took the new cherry but still did not get any help. The bowlers failed to bowl probing lines and lengths and the English batters took full advantage of it until Mohammed Siraj provided India with a crucial breakthrough scalping Dawid Malan. They will have something to celebrate about heading into the break. Can India scalp a few more? Join us back at 1600 local (1500 GMT) for the last session of the day to find out.

England dominate further and extend their lead to 220 runs. Root and Malan looked very comfortable in the middle and scored runs freely. For both sides, the picture is clear, India need wickets while England will look to pile on as many runs as possible. Join us at 1340 local (1240 GMT) for another enthralling session.

The story of the bland pitch continues! The Indian bowlers toiled hard, but they hardly got any support from the pitch. There was a lack of movement in the first session. But it was not an issue for Shami. He found the breakthrough by getting the better of Burns. After that, there was a patch when Hameed and Malan were negotiating well, and India were losing their spirit. But then, Jadeja struck and got his first wicket of this series. He departed the set batsman, Hameed and brought some ray of hope in the Indian camp.

England still with the advantage, but they certainly have lost some grip off it. Hameed and Burns picked things well from where they left off last evening. But they were not able to hit the runs as freely as they did on Day 1. Both the batters were eyeing for a century, but both fell short. Burns was the first one to depart. While Hameed looked solid in the middle but got knocked out by a ripper from Jadeja just a short time before Lunch. The skipper, Root and Malan are in the middle, they will come with an intention to bat for as long as they can post Lunch.

Although, England lost a couple of wickets before Lunch, but they still have an upper hand in this game. The Three Lions lead by 104 runs. The Indians bowler kept things tight, but the pitch did not offer them any help. They will be happy with the two wickets. This session looked to be a shared one between the two sides.

We begin with some bad news -  Former England Captain, Ted Dexter passed away today at the age of 86 and England will wear black armbands as a mark of respect. May his soul rest in peace.

While Hameed showed his caliber, Rory Burns has supported him well from the other end and would be great if the birthday boy can get a ton to his name in front of the home crowd. What better way to celebrate your birthday than getting a ton in front of your fans, right?

Haseeb Hameed didn't live up to the expectations in the second Test at Lord's but he has certainly silenced the critics in the third Test. He is unbeaten at 60 and will be rearing to get to a three-digit figure.

Hello and a warm welcome to Day 2 of the third Test between England and India. The visitors had a horror day as they were bundled out for only 78 runs in the first innings. On the other hand, what a turnaround it was for England after the Lord's Test. The Three Lions didn't put a foot wrong and are in a commendable position ending Day 1 with 120/0. While England will look to solidify their lead from here on, it will be interesting to see whether India can make a comeback or not. Stay tuned for further updates.
... Day 2, Session 1 ...

Right then. Absolutely England's day, the first one. They have a decent lead to their name and also have all the wickets in hand, and so, they will look to swell that lead up to a big score. India, meanwhile, have a task on their hands and will want to bowl better on Day 2 and take a couple of quick wickets to push the hosts on the back foot. The action on Day 2 will begin at 11 am local (10 am GMT), but the build-up will begin earlier. Do join us then. Cheers!

Just not India's day, really. Neither with the bat nor with the ball. Apart from Rohit Sharma and to some extent, Ajinkya Rahane, none of their batters had any sort of impact. They folded quite easily and did not show any sort of fight. There was more onus on the bowlers to deliver since their batters could not, but alas, it was not meant to be. The Indian pacers could not extract anything from this deck and they failed to even get a single wicket. It was not that they bowled too poorly, but they just did not find any sort of success. A poor day, from the point of view of the Indians.

England started off brilliantly and have maintained the same tempo throughout the day. It all started when James Anderson removed KL Rahul in the very first over of the day and after that, there was no looking back for them. Anderson took two more and after a decent stand between Rohit and Rahane, the trio of Curran, Robinson, and Overton took quick wickets and bundled India out for just 78. With the bat, England have had their fair share of issues, but their new opening duo, Hameed and Burns took time to settle in, but when they felt comfortable, they started scoring runs freely and both got to their fifties as well, as they ended the day with a lead of 42 to their name.

This has been an exceptional day for the hosts as they have ticked all the boxes and ended the Day with not only their noses, but also their faces in front. Nothing seemed to go right for India and they will look to head back, get a good night's rest and come back out on Day 2 with renewed energy and excitement.

There seems to be an issue with the landing area and the umpires decide that it is time for DRINKS. It has been a great session of play for England as their openers have braved the challenge and have also looked very solid out in the middle. They have not lost a single wicket so far and are cruising right now, just behind by 20 runs. India's bowlers have not tasted any success yet and they will want to break this stand as soon as possible, and snare a couple more before Stumps. Let's see how this final phase of play on Day 1 pans out.

Length ball, jagging back in from off. Haseeb Hameed gets behind the line to block it out.
Length ball, coming in from outside off. Haseeb Hameed leaves it alone.

An inswinger from Ishant, around the off pole. Haseeb Hameed comes forward and blocks it solidly.

We are back for the third and final session on Day 1! A big session of play for both teams. Around 40 overs left in the day and India will look to make the most of the same, whereas, England would look to bat it out nicely and not lose too many wickets. Haseeb Hameed and Rory Burns walk out to resume their innings. Jasprit Bumrah to begin with the ball.
... Day 1, Session 3 ...

A solid session of cricket from England. Firstly, they came after the Lunch break and decided to make life difficult for the Indian batters. Once they snared the big wicket of Rohit Sharma, the other batters followed suit and they were bundled out for just 78. Their openers, Haseeb Hameed and Rory Burns did well to deal with the challenge until the Tea break and have cut the deficit down to 57. Not much to write about India's display as their batters folded like a pack of cards. Even their bowlers were not able to hand a blow by snaring a wicket or two and they are on the back foot after the first two sessions. India will look to come out in the third session and take a couple of quick wickets, whereas, the English openers would look to continue in their merry way. Join us for the final session on Day 1 at 4 pm local (3 pm GMT).
Short of a length, around off. Rory Burns stays back and defends it out solidly. THAT WILL BE TEA ON DAY 1!
Good-length ball, on off. Rory Burns gets behind the line to block this one.
Good-length ball, around off. Rory Burns taps it towards cover.

Maiden over! An inswinger, starting from outside off. Haseeb Hameed shoulders arms to it.

On a length, around off. Haseeb Hameed defends it out off the front foot.

Right then, this Test series is interestingly poised now. India landed a heavy punch at Lord's but England have responded with an innings victory. One thing is for sure though, the momentum is not going to stay in one corner, it will keep oscillating. How will India respond to this big loss? Do join us for the 4th Test starting on 2nd September at The Oval to find out. The action will begin at 11 am local (10 am GMT) but you can join us in advance for the build-up. Cheers!

Ollie Robinson is chosen for the Man of the Match award! He says that it is very special and he has dreamt about this as a kid. Adds that he enjoyed bowling here and used the conditions well and getting a 5-fer in an England victory is special. Mentions that it is an honour to play with Anderson and he keeps learning from Jimmy. Tells that it was nice to get Kohli's wicket as he also hit him for a couple of boundaries in the over. Further adds that the plan was the same to Kohli, to bowl in the channel outside off, get it to nip away, and hope that he nicks one. Shares that he feels fine and it was good to get a break between the second Test and the third Test.

The captain of England, Joe Root, says that it was a clinical performance from their bowlers and they put pressure early on and from the outset, they had a good opportunity to step up and they did that well. Adds that they knew they were capable of putting in displays like this and they just need consistency and lauds his openers for their stand in the first innings. Feels that they hung in there and managed to get results with the second new ball on Day 4. On Anderson, Root says that he sets a wonderful example for the rest of the bowling group, and to consistently perform as he does, is wonderful. On Malan, Joe tells that he played beautifully, and once he got going, he looked fluent and it is great to see him play well. Says that as a batter, you should be ready to come out and score runs whenever needed. Shares that it is special to get a hundred in his home ground and hopes that he carries the same forward. On Robinson, Root replies that he has been exceptional and hopes that his form continues for longer. Opines that Curran is a talented player even though he has not performed at his best in this series. Adds that Curran had an impact late in the first innings too, with the ball. On Buttler's availability for the last two Tests, due to paternity leave, Root says that they will find out in the next couple of days. On the crowd, he says that he always gets a wonderful reception and thanks all the fans for their support.

Virat Kohli, the Indian skipper, says that it was basically down to scoreboard pressure and they were always up against it after getting all out for 78. Adds that they knew it would be hard but opines that they did well on Day 3 and they got a couple of crucial partnerships which set them up, but the pressure from the English pacers troubled them on Day 4. On the first innings, he says that it was bizarre as the pitch was good for batting as demonstrated by the English openers later on. Tells that the pressure was relentless and he feels that it's a combination of bad decision-making from the batters and a quality bowling display from England. Laughs and says that he does not have any regrets with the toss and feels that their batters need to make better decisions and they were just not on the money in this game. On India's batting depth, Kohli replies that the top order has to do enough to give the lower order something to step up. Adds that as a batting group, they need to stay confident and they do not want their lower order to bail them out of a tough spot every time. Tells that they need to assess the surface and also the forecast before deciding on the XI in the next game but at the same time emphasizes that the template to play with 4 fast bowlers is working. Shares that they are confident and they have bounced back many times in the past and they take a lot of pride in trying to correct their errors.
Stay tuned for the presentation...

You don't win many Test matches after getting bundled out in the first two sessions of a Test match. India suffered that fate on Day 1 and to compound their misery, the misfiring English top order chose to return to form. Haseeb Hameed and Rory Burns shut the doors on India by forming a century stand and after that Dawid Malan and Joe Root extended the English dominance. The Indian bowling was blunted successfully and once the hosts gained a 354-run lead, the writing was on the wall for India.

India fought bravely on Day 3. Rohit Sharma, Cheteshwar Pujara, Virat Kohli put their hands up and reignited hope in the Indian camp. The big deficit was narrowed down to 139 with 8 wickets in hand and all the eyes were on Pujara and Kohli this morning. England had the advantage to operate with the second new ball and the pair of Ollie Robinson and James Anderson ran amok. 8 wickets went down in one session (7 in the span of 54 minutes) and India's misery with the bat was exposed once again in this Test match.

England have stormed back into this Test series. They have levelled it 1-1 and that sets up for a brilliant last two games. The English players are celebrating on the ground, jumping in joy and the crowd is loving every bit of it. After the high of the Lord's Test, India's flight has come down crashing. Cricket is a great leveller.

OUT! EDGED AND CAUGHT! It is all done! There is the game. It has not taken long for England in the morning session on Day 4 to wrap the game up. Brilliant work from England and Overton finishes proceedings. Craig Overton bowls this one on a length, closer to the off pole, it lands and shapes away. Mohammed Siraj looks to block but the outside edge is induced. Jonny Bairstow, at second slip, dives to his right and pouches this. ENGLAND WIN BY AN INNINGS AND 76 RUNS AND LEVEL THE SERIES 1-1!
Commentary.Howout: c Jonny Bairstow b Craig Overton

Commentary.Commentary: Overton slips this down the leg side, Siraj tries to flick but misses.
Mohammed Siraj is the last batsman for India.

OUT! EDGED AND CAUGHT! Overton joins the party now! Brilliant work from him and another Indian batter takes a sad, long walk back to the shed. Jadeja walks back and there goes India's last shot at avoiding an innings defeat. On a length by Overton, landing closer to off and then leaving the batter. Ravindra Jadeja looks to defend but that proves to be his undoing, as the outside edge is caught. Another catch that Jos Buttler is not going to drop. England are one more wicket away from levelling the series.
Commentary.Howout: c Jos Buttler b Craig Overton

A touch short of fuller length, around off, Bumrah dabs it back onto the deck.
Tossed up, outside off, this is jammed out to the off side.
Short again, width offered outside off, slapped to sweeper cover for one. Hands the strike back to Bumrah.
Short, on off, tapped to the point region.
Loopy, landing full on off, spins in, Bumrah gets low and slog-sweeps it to deep mid-wicket for a run.

FOUR! Third in a row! Craig Overton comes 'round the wicket and hurls a shortish ball, offering width outside off, Jadeja again waits for the ball to arrive and then just dabs it past the diving gully fielder. India are behind by 78, whereas, England need 2 more wickets.

FOUR! Another good shot. Placed it nicely this time. Slightly short, outside off, angling away, he waits for the ball to come to him and just pushes this one past the gully fielder. Jadeja wants to save India at least from the embarrassment of an innings defeat. Can he do it?

FOUR! That's played nicely. Jadeja is getting some boundaries here, but it does not look like it will make any substantial difference. Overpitched this time, on off, Jadeja punches this with hard hands through the mid off region.
Around off, fuller, pushed to the cover region.
An action replay of the previous delivery.

Slants a length delivery across the southpaw, an easy leave for Jadeja.
Moeen tosses this one too, lands it around off, the ball hits the deck and spins in as Bumrah presses forward. The ball takes the inside edge, but hits Bumrah on his pad and falls safely on the deck.
A single as this is tucked to the mid-wicket region.

SIX! Jadeja is not going to hang around. He will try to get some quick runs and apply some pressure on the English bowlers. This is bowled fuller again, around middle and spinning away, Ravindra Jadeja jumps out. Thwacks this one over the bowler for a biggie.

OUT! EDGED AND CAUGHT! Wicket number 5 for Robinson and he is on fire! The Indian batters just keep following each other back to the shed. None of them are showing any sort of resistance. We are nearing the curtains on this game. Just 2 more wickets away, are the Three Lions!

Can they pick the remaining wickets before Lunch?

NOT OUT! Missing the leg stump. Identical to the last delivery, on a full length around middle and angling down, Shami again fails to flick and wears it on his pads. The appeal is made and this time the finger has gone up. Shami takes the referral. Nothing on the UltraEdge but the Ball Tracker confirms that it's missing the sticks.

Review time! Mohammed Shami has been given out for LBW and he takes the review. Clear daylight between bat and ball, confirms the UltraEdge. Shami survives as Ball Tracker shows that the ball was missing the wickets.

On a length, angling away from around off, Ravindra Jadeja looks to drive but only manages an outside edge, which goes aerially past Moeen Ali at point, and runs away to the ropes. Moeen probably had all his weight on the left leg and hence didn't get enough time to react with a dive.
Fuller, way outside off, RJ shows no interest in playing at that.

FOUR! Good shot down the ground. Not a lot to be happy about for India, but this shot will lift the mood ever-so-slightly. On a length, around the off pole, Ravindra Jadeja just pushes this gently through mid off.
Around off, on a length, kept out by Jadeja.

Huge shout for an lbw, not given. A big inswinger from Robinson, landing on a good length and jagging back in sharply. Shami shuffles across a bit in defense but misses. He is rapped on the pads, they appeal but the finger stays down. Maybe, too high. End of a superb over by Robinson.
England are well into the tail-enders now. Don't know if we can call Mohammed Shami a tail-ender due to his knock in the last game. But, in any case, Shami walks out now. India behind by 115 runs.

OUT! CAUGHT AT SLIPS! Pant gets out defending. Hmm... Maybe, that's why he was swinging his bat. Ollie Robinson has shown great discipline this morning. His lines have been exemplary and he has altered his lengths superbly as well. This one is served in the channel outside off and the natural angle of the bowler takes it away from the left-hander. Pant could have left it alone but he wants to feel the ball. Goes after it with a defensive bat and edges it to third slip. Craig Overton has safe hands and England are four wickets away now from making it 1-1 in the series.
Commentary.Howout: c Craig Overton b Ollie Robinson

Commentary.Commentary: Fuller, closer to off, Pant is standing outside the crease to smother the movement and defends it down.
Around leg, on a length, Pant fails to work it around and is hit high on the pads.
On a length, around middle, this time Pant stays compact in his defense and blocks it down on the surface.

Swing and a miss! Pant will bat on his terms, regardless of the situation, he wants to attack the bowlers. Robinson angles across a shortish delivery, outside off, Pant jumps down the track, tries to slap it through the line but misses. Maybe, Rishabh Pant doesn't trust his defense enough to survive this moment.
India in some trouble now. Half their side back in the shed. Now, Ravindra Jadeja trudges out into the middle.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Third wicket goes down for India this morning and England are celebrating big. Needless from Rahane. Anderson delivers it on a length and just outside off, it lands and moves away slightly, Rahane should have looked to defend it close to his body but needless hangs his bat out in defense. The ball moves away, takes a thick outside edge and goes to the keeper. As soon as Jos Buttler catches it, Joe Root jumps in delight. The crowd is loving it. India have now lost 5 wickets and staring down the barrel.
Commentary.Howout: c Jos Buttler b James Anderson

Commentary.Commentary: Fuller and on off, angling in, Rahane flicks it off his pads but finds mid-wicket.
Around off on a length, the batsman has just watchfully blocked this out.
Fuller this time, around middle and leg, Pant walks forward and flicks as his bat turns in his hands. The ball rolls in the gap at mid-wicket and they cross. Rishabh Pant is off the mark.
Anderson delivers it on a good length, around middle, Pant is on the charge as he tries to defend. Misses the ball and is hit near the box. Is this smart batting or reckless?
On a length, close to off, Rahane stays back and taps it down to covers for a run.
Rishabh Pant walks in next.

OUT! EDGED AND TAKEN! There it is! You are never settled as a batter in England and even though Kohli just got to his fifty in this over, he has to depart. Joe Root takes the catch and it is quite poetic how the English skipper plays a part in removing the Indian captain. Root seems pretty happy with his work. Back of a length, just around the off pole, the ball lands and holds its line slightly as Virat Kohli looks to block this one out with an angled bat. The ball catches the outside edge and goes to the left of Joe Root at first slip, who moves that side and makes no mistake. Two quick wickets and India are on the back foot now. Both the overnight batters have been sent packing and England are smelling blood. India are still behind by 117 runs!
Commentary.Howout: c Joe Root b Ollie Robinson

Commentary.Commentary: FOUR! Save your legs, that was going to race away to the boundary. Overpitched slightly, around off, Kohli shows the full face of the bat and beats the diving mid on fielder (James Anderson) to his left, with a punch and gets his second boundary of the over.
Good length again, fourth stump channel, Virat Kohli presses forward and hangs his bat in defense, but the ball shapes away late and beats the outside edge.
Good-length ball, on off, tapped to point this time.
Virat Kohli has just watchfully blocked this out.

FOUR! Fifty for Virat Kohli! His first 50 of the series and he will be looking to turn this into a big one. Fuller-length ball, around off, Virat Kohli goes back and whips this through mid-wicket for a boundary.
Length, outside off, shaping inwards, Rahane lets this pass by him, to Buttler.
Around off, fuller this time, Rahane prods ahead and pushes to covers.
On a length, outside off, Rahane looks to defend but gets beaten on this occasion.
Outside off, no shot offered.
Ajinkya Rahane has just watchfully blocked this out.
Short of a length, on off, tapped to covers for one.
Angled around off and middle, this is knocked to the mid on region.
Around off, tapped to the off side.
FOUR! Wow! Well played by Rahane. A half-volley, around off this time, Ajinkya Rahane gets low and drives this one wonderfully through the cover-point region for a boundary.
Outside off, left alone by Rahane.
That is defended solidly off the front foot.
The batsman has just watchfully blocked this out.

Edged and gone! Anderson seems to have found the outside edge. The finger has gone up. England are celebrating. Virat Kohli has a word with his partner and takes the DRS. The UltraEdge shows there is daylight between bat and ball, the spike is for the bat clipping the pads. The decision is reversed. DRS at its best.

NOT OUT! A brilliant decision to take the review and the on-field decision has been overturned. England were over the moon but they have to be brought back here. The sound was off Virat's bat hitting his pad, not off the ball coming off the edge. On a length this time, in the zone of uncertainty outside off, Virat Kohli looks to push at this but the ball whistles through to Buttler, who takes it and appeals. The umpire raises his finger and the roof has been raised at Leeds. Virat Kohli turns around and looks to walk back, but he turns as Ajinkya Rahane from the other end persuades him to take the review. Virat is unsure if he edged that. The replays roll in and it turned out really well for India, as UltraEdge shows that Kohli hit his bat to his pad and there was no edge. Kohli survives.
In the fourth stump channel, length, Virat Kohli shoulders arms this time.
Around off, pushed to covers this time.

SHOUT FOR AN LBW! Back of a length, around off, Virat Kohli looks to defend, but the ball shoots up and hits Kohli high on the thigh pad. An appeal but turned down. Jimmy does not want the review. Root is looking around, hoping that someone will persuade him to take the review, but it does not happen. A good decision as the replays show that the ball was missing the wickets.

BEATEN! Wonderful delivery from Jimmy. This was a similar delivery to Virat's first-innings dismissal. Fuller in length, around off, the ball shapes away late as Virat Kohli looks to play straight, but he fails to get bat on ball this time.
Closer to off, length this time, Virat just dabs this one towards point.
Around off, on a length, Ajinkya defends this one out solidly.
Outside off, it lands and shapes away, AR makes no movement to play at this as he leaves.
FOUR! Confident shot from Rahane and this is the first boundary of the morning. Overpitched delivery, closer to off, Ajinkya Rahane pushes this one gently through the mid off region for a boundary.
Lands it on a length, in the fourth stump channel, the ball jags back in quickly, as Ajinkya Rahane taps this one to the off side.
First runs for Virat Kohli this morning! On a length, angling in, around off, Kohli drops this to the cover region and crosses ends.
On a fullish length, outside off, shapes away as the Indian captain makes a leave.
Anderson targets the stumps with an inswinger, landing on a length around off, Rahane meets it with a dead bat as he blocks it from the crease.
Lands it on a length and just outside off, a good leave by Rahane.
Inward movement on this delivery, it starts from a length around middle, Virat fails to work it around and is hit on the pads. They cross for a leg bye.
Beaten all ends up! Anderson dishes it out around off, on a fuller length and gets it to move away, Kohli commits himself on the front foot, tries to push inside the line and is beaten.
Rahane gets off the mark. On a good length around off, Rahane pushes it defensively to the off side, finds the gap at covers and crosses for a run.
It's on a length and around off, Rahane defends it from the back foot to the off side.
Around off on a good length, Kohli defends it from the back foot to the off side.
Fullish and just outside off, Kohli allows it through to the keeper. Called a no ball for overstepping.
On middle and leg, shaping down, Rahane tries to flick but it takes his pads and deflects down to fine leg for a leg bye. There's the first run for India this morning.
Good first ball to Ajinkya. On a length and close to off, Rahane defends it from the inside half of his bat to the leg side.
Ajinkya Rahane makes his way out into the middle.

OUT! PUJARA IS GONE! Robinson has hit the jackpot. He comes up with a full delivery around off, shaping back in, Pujara offers no shot and takes it on his back pad. They appeal but the umpire stays still. Root has a word with his bowler and the keeper. This time he goes for the referral in time. Remember, the impact won't be an issue here as the batter was not offering any shot. The Ball Tracker rolls in and it shows three reds. Huge roar from the English players, they have got an early success this morning and it's the big wicket of Pujara. Surely, there was an error in judgement from Cheteshwar Pujara, he was undone first by the fuller length and then by the extravagant inward movement. To worsen the situation, he was hit on the back pad. Had that been on the front pad, it could have headed over the stumps. Once again he misses out on scoring a century.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Ollie Robinson

Commentary.Commentary: Review time! Joe Root opts for a review, for this LBW appeal against Cheteshwar Pujara! Since there is no shot offered, there is no need for UltraEdge. Time for the Ball Tracker, replays roll in and it is THREE REDS. Pujara goes back without getting his ton and England have struck early.
On a good length around off, Pujara defends it from the back foot back towards the bowler. Unlike Anderson, Ollie is making the batsman play more.
Angling in from around off, Pujara has his defensive bat down as he keeps it out safely to mid-wicket.
On a length and close to off, it straightens from there, Kohli has to play at that and he taps it down to point. Third maiden of the morning.
Identical to the last delivery, Anderson is playing on Kohli's patience here. Virat is in no mood to commit himself to any kind of a shot.
Angles it in around off and takes it away with the seam movement, Virat lifts his bat and allows it through to the keeper.
Anderson remains disciplined in his approach, bowling it in the channel outside off, an outswinger, Kohli also stays disciplined as he leaves.
Anderson gets close to the off stump line this time, Kohli does well to cover his stumps as he allows it through.
Anderson bowls it on a good length and in the corridor outside off, Kohli shoulders arms.
Ollie Robinson returns to bowl in the channel outside off, shaping away off the seam, Pujara is forward to cover the line as he makes a leave. A couple of maidens to begin the day's play.
Slips a full ball down the leg side, Pujara tries to flick but misses.
Oohhh...that wasn't too far away from the off pole. Robinson lands it on a good length and close to off, this one just holds its line and Pujara allows it through. Brave leave in the end.
Fuller again, a bit close to off but not close enough to bother the batsman. It lands and moves away, Cheteshwar Pujara just sees it through to the keeper.
Fuller in length and outside off, there is a hint of away movement, Pujara watches the line closely and then makes a leave.
Robinson delivers it very full and around off, Pujara pushes it out from the bottom half of his bat to covers. He is on 91 and would love to get a hundred and end his lean patch.

Anderson makes Kohli play. Serves it on middle and off, Kohli plays late and drops it with gentle hands in front of the cordon. Looks for a run but a loud shout of no comes from Pujara. Day 4 begins with a maiden over.
Ollie Robinson to share the new cherry from the other end!
Another good delivery and another good leave from the Indian captain. On and around off, moving away off the seam, Kohli is very patient at the moment.
Jimmy keeps probing around off. Close to off and shapes away after landing on a length, Kohli covers his stumps and allows it through.
Anderson is sticking to the line outside off, a gentle away movement on this occasion, Kohli continues to leave it.
In the channel outside off, on a length again, not much movement on this occasion, Virat has nothing to do with it as he leaves it alone.
Anderson is right on the button! Starts with serving it on a length close to off, shaping away, Kohli shoulders arms.

Right then. Time to start the action on Day 4. It is an absolute beauty of a setting for a Test match. A sunny morning, finally. All the Indian fans will be happy to see the ground baked in sunshine and light. Virat Kohli and Cheteshwar Pujara make their way out firstly and will look to continue their good work from Day 3. The English players follow them out and spread out to their respective positions. As expected, England have opted to take the second new ball and it is James Anderson who will be making use of it, first-up. Here he is, running in...

PITCH - Dominic Cork starts by sharing that it's 18 degrees at the moment. Tells that this pitch has been good, there was some swing and seam on the first day, but it is a very good pitch for batting. Mentions that the groundsmen have made sure that the pitch stays together. Talks about the rough patches visible on the surface but overall, Cork believes it's a belter for batting.

WEATHER - It is not every day that you see this sort of weather in England. It is BRIGHT and SUNNY at the moment and the ground is baked in sunshine. Anderson might not be loving looking at the sky right now, because he does not have his favoured cloudy conditions, which would have helped his cause. The Indians would be hoping for this weather to hang around till the end of the day.

The assignments for both teams are pretty clear heading into the penultimate day of this Test. It looked like the game was done and dusted when England had a humongous lead to their name, but India, to their credit, have batted way better than they did on Day 1 and the onus now lies on Pujara and skipper, Kohli. They have cut the lead down to just 139 runs and will want to quickly cut into the deficit. But, they have a problem on their hands - the second new ball. If Anderson and Robinson use the new cherry and wreak havoc on the Indians, then this game could be wrapped up today itself. But, if India can navigate the first hour of play, then they can score runs freely. The first session will really be an important one, as it shall give us an idea as to which team is on top.

Hello, folks! A warm welcome to day number 4 in the third Test between England and India. After having the first 2 days belong to England, the visitors finally made their presence felt on Day 3 as they batted well and hard. They took a while to see off the opening spell from Anderson and Robinson, but after that Pujara and Kohli batted splendidly and ensured that they cut down the deficit to as much as possible and will be looking to continue their good work. It should be another interesting day of cricket.
... Day 4, Session 1 ...

Right then. India have done well on Day 3 and would look to continue the same heading into the penultimate day of the Test. England, meanwhile, will look to use the second new ball well and make some inroads, before India cut into their lead. If England does well with the second new ball, then the game can end on Day 4 itself. But if India can see off the new ball, then runs would flow as they flowed on Day 2 when England batted. So, it is fair to say that the first session could decide the fate of this game. The action on Day 4 will begin at 11 am local (10 am GMT), but, the buildup will begin earlier. Do join us then. Cheers and take care!

Not the sort of day England would have wanted after having 2 days filled with goodness and success. They would have envisioned that they bowl as they did on Day 1 and run through the Indian batters but that never happened. In the first spell, India were slightly lucky as they played and missed quite a few of balls and the English pacers really made life tough for India, but after that, they could not continue with the same momentum. Ollie Robinson and Craig Overton got a wicket each and were good too. James Anderson did not have a wicket to his name, but he probed well with his line and length. Sam Curran again was slightly wayward and did not find his rhythm. Overall, not the best outing for the Brits.

India's middle order has been pretty fragile and the form of Cheteshwar Pujara and Virat Kohli has been on everyone's mind, but these two showed everyone why they are the stalwarts in the Indian team, as they raised an unbeaten stand of 99 runs, before the light did not allow them to continue. Pujara, especially, has been under the scanner but he is into the 90s and will be looking to come out on Day 4 and reach his ton. In his company, Kohli is on 45 and will be looking to march on and cut the deficit down quickly enough.

India started Day 3 perfectly, not taking long to remove the last 2 wickets early on Day 3 and then seeing off the ferocious new-ball spells from Anderson and Robinson. Rahul lost his wicket and India looked to be slipping, but the duo of Rohit Sharma and Cheteshwar Pujara batted through the entire post-Lunch session and also raised an 82-run stand, before Sharma's knock was ended by Ollie Robinson.

Another great day of cricket between these two. After 2 days where the hosts have enjoyed most of the success, it is India who have finally had their say in this game and they will be pleased with their work on Day 3. The last two sessions on Day 3 have seen India bat well and also stack up the runs at a good pace, as they end the day, behind by 139 runs.
England want to take the second new ball. But the light is not good enough for the pacers to bowl. So, the umpires have decided to call for Stumps on Day 3.
Tossed up, outside off. Cheteshwar Pujara comes down the track and pads it away.
Cheteshwar Pujara comes down the track and drives it through covers. The man from deep cover runs to his right and dives to keep it to two. Cheteshwar Pujara moves into the 90s now.
Shorter ball, on off. Kohli works it to the leg side for one.
Flatter ball, on off. Blocked out.
Tossed up, outside off. Kohli gets in a good stride and blocks it.
Tossed up, on off. Kohli gets forward and blocks it.
Loopy ball, on off. Blocked out.
This stays low! Loopy ball, outside off. Pujara plays for the spin but the ball goes straight and stays a bit low. Buttler cannot collect it and the batters get two byes.
Flatter ball, way outside off. Pujara leaves it.
Flatter ball, around off. Punched away.
Loopy ball, on leg. Worked to the leg side.
FOUR! Almost takes out the umpire this time! How's the light now, Root? Short ball, on leg. Pujara pulls it hard. The square leg umpire sways away from it in time and the ball races to the fence.
Tossed up, on off. Kohli blocks it out.
FOUR! Short ball and punished! Root bowls the leg spinner now, but he bowls it very short. Kohli goes back in his crease and pulls it past deep mid-wicket for a boundary.
Loopy ball, on off. Pushed back to the bowler.
Cheteshwar Pujara comes down the track and taps it to the off side for one.
Tossed up, outside off. Kohli drives it to deep cover for one.
Shorter ball, on off. Blocked out.
Tossed up, outside off. Pujara gets to the pitch and then leaves it.
Shorter ball, on off. Pushed to the off side.
Flatter ball, on leg. Worked to the leg side.
Tossed up, on off. Cheteshwar Pujara looks to defend with his bat and pad together. The ball goes towards short leg, who takes it, but it came off the pad.
Loopy ball, around off. Pujara stays in his crease and blocks it.
Flatter ball, on off. Pushed to deep cover for one. That brings up 200 for India.
Shorter ball, on off. Kohli goes back and works it past square leg for one.
Shorter again, outside off. Pushed to mid off now.
Shorter ball, outside off. Cut away to deep cover for one.
Flatter ball, outside off. Pujara offers his pads after striding forward.
Tossed up, outside off. Kohli gets to the pitch of the ball and pushes it to deep cover for one.
Shorter ball, on off. Kohli stays back and works it to mid-wicket.
Flatter ball, on off. Worked to the leg side.
Tossed up, outside off. Kohli drives it hard to the fielder at deep extra cover.
Shorter ball, on off. Kohli works it towards short leg.
Loopy ball, on off. Kohli gets on the front foot and blocks it.
Cheteshwar Pujara comes down the track and clips it past square leg for another single.
Shorter ball, on off. Kohli works it off the back foot to deep mid-wicket for one.
Flatter ball, outside off. Left alone.
Flatter ball, outside off. Pushed to covers.

That has turned sharply! Tossed up, outside off. It lands in the rough and turns back in. Kohli looks to block but the ball goes through the gate and goes just over the stumps. Even the keeper cannot collect it and the batters get a bye.
Shorter ball, outside off. Kohli looks to push it away but gets the inside edge back on the pads.
Shorter ball, on leg. Pujara works it to the leg side for one.
Full ball, on leg. Whipped towards deep square leg. Kohli runs the first one hard, but there is no second one there.
Tossed up, outside off. Pujara gets his front foot to the pitch of the ball and leaves it.

FOUR! Poor ball and punished by Cheteshwar Pujara! Shorter ball, wide outside off. Pujara frees his arms and cuts it past backward point. The fielder chases it but the ball wins the race. He moves to 81 now.
Loopy ball, on leg. Worked to the leg side.

Virat Kohli comes down the track and blocks it out.
Flatter ball, on off. Pujara blocks it out.
Darted on the pads. Tucked to the leg side by Pujara.

Flatter ball, outside off. Pushed away to the off side.
Fuller ball, on off. Blocked out.
Flatter ball, around off. Pujara stays in his crease and blocks it.
Shorter ball, around off. Kohli pushes it to mid on.
Tossed up, on off. Kohli blocks it out.

The reason why Joe Root has decided to bring himself on and take off his pacers is because, in between overs, the umpires decided that the light was not good enough to continue, but the English skipper assured the umpires that he would not use his pacers and only the spinners would bowl.
Full ball, on off. Pushed to mid on.
Flatter ball, on off. Pushed to mid-wicket.
Tossed up, outside off. Kohli prods forward and blocks it.
Flatter ball, outside off. Kohli goes back and blocks it out.
Cheteshwar Pujara comes down the track and blocks this one out.
Darted on the pads. Pujara works it straight to square leg.
Tossed up, outside off. Pujara comes down the track and whips it straight towards mid-wicket.
Loopy ball, on off. Kohli eases it to long on for one.
Fuller ball, on off. Pushed to covers.
Loopy ball, outside off. Left alone.
Shorter ball, on off. Kohli pulls it to deep mid-wicket. Runs are flowing easily for these two here.
Tossed up, on off. Virat Kohli blocks it off the front foot.
Shorter ball, outside off. Slapped to deep cover for one.
Shorter ball, on off. Kohli works it to deep square leg for one.
Cheteshwar Pujara comes down the track and clips it to deep square leg for one.

Fuller ball, around off. Kohli works it to the leg side.

Anderson bowls it full now, on off. Kohli is solid in his defence.
Back of a length, around off. Kohli pushes it to covers.

NOT OUT! Tossed up, outside off. Kohli looks to block but the ball goes past the edge. Buttler whips the bails off and the TV umpire is called in. They first check for caught behind, but there is no bat on that one. Then, comes the check for stumping. Replays show that Kohli has his back foot just behind the line, so not out is the decision.
Shorter ball, around off. Blocked out.
Has Virat Kohli been stumped? Nopes. The replays show that his foot was grounded, when the bails came off. Will be not out.

Tossed up, outside off, Kohli came down the track and looked to flick. But the ball pitched, spun in a little, took the inside edge, hit the pad and lobbed. But well wide of short leg, to his left, towards mid-wicket. Kohli wanted a single but was sent back.
Shorter ball, outside off. Pujara slaps it to deep cover for one.
FOUR! Top shot by Kohli! Anderson bowls it full and outside off. Kohli leans into it and drives it through covers for a boundary.

Around off, pushed to the point region.
Pujara puts on his skates again and his clip finds the mid-wicket fielder.
Floated outside off, CP dances down and looks to defend, as the ball spins in and pings him on his pad.
A single as this fuller ball is dug out through the cover region.
Gives it a lot of air, fuller outside off, this is jammed out to the mid off fielder.
Moeen Ali is back on.
Maiden for Jimmy! Around off, worked to the leg side.
Slightly outside the off pole, Pujara just taps this to the off side.

An action replay of the previous ball.

Drinks break. This has been another good passage of play for India. Slowly and steadily, they are chipping down the deficit and both these batters are looking in really good touch. England would be keen on breaking this stand putting the Indian middle order under pressure. Here comes James Anderson to try and break this stand.
Kohli gets a couple of runs now. A half-volley near the pads now, VK whips this to deep mid-wicket and comes back for the second run.
On middle, dropped towards mid-wicket for a quick run.

Good-length delivery on the pads, nicely flicked to deep square leg for a run.

Back of a length, around off. Kohli blocks it.
Fuller ball, angling across the off pole. Pujara gets forward and then leaves it.
Curran serves a length ball, right in the line of the stumps. Pujara pushes it back to the bowler.

Fuller ball, around off. Pujara pushes it to cover.

Full ball, on off. Pujara looks to block but gets the inside edge back on the pads.

FOUR! Lovely shot. Full ball, on off. Pujara drives it down the ground. The man from mid off gets to his right and dives but cannot get there. The ball runs to the fence and Pujara moves to 70.
Back of a length, outside off. Pujara leaves it yet again.
Full ball, wide outside off. Pujara covers his stumps and then leaves it.

Full ball, on off. Kohli looks to drive but gets it from the inner half to the mid on fielder.

Fuller ball, right on the off pole. Kohli blocks it back to the bowler. No ball called as Ollie Robinson oversteps.

Outswinger but this starts way outside off. Kohli covers his stumps and lets this one go.

FOUR! Looks like James Anderson got frustrated watching Pujara leave everything and hence, serves an inswinger around middle and leg, easy pickings for Cheteshwar Pujara as he clips this to the square leg fence.
Again, outside off, length, Pujara wants nothing to do with it.

Around off, kept out.

FOUR! Lovely. That's the vintage Kohli that we all know. In the fourth-stump channel, on a drivable length, Virat Kohli shows the full face of the bat and creams this through covers. Moves to 10 from 15 balls.

Short of a length, in the fourth stump channel, Cheteshwar Pujara dabs this one past the slip cordon. Haseeb Hameed chases after this and pulls the ball back, before it touches the ropes. Three taken this time.

NO BALL! Ollie Robinson oversteps this time. On a length, around off, Virat Kohli looks to flick but closes the face of his bat early. The outside edge is induced and the ball goes to covers for one. Kohli is off the mark!

Short ball, on off. Pujara ducks under this one with ease.
Robinson bowls it on a length and tempts Kohli to play at it. But the Indian skipper leaves it.

The Indian skipper, Virat Kohli, strides out into the middle. A lot of responsibility on his shoulders. Will he deliver?

OUT! LBW! Umpire's call sends Rohit Sharma back! He is very disappointed. Ollie Robinson strikes just after Tea and this is exactly what England wanted. It has come against the run of play as well, as Rohit was looking very settled out in the middle. Ollie Robinson fires a full ball, angling in, on middle. Sharma looks to whip it away but the ball comes back in just a touch and hits him on the pads. England put in a big appeal and the umpire raises the finger. Sharma reviews this. There is no bat on that one but Ball Tracker has umpire's call on wickets hitting the outer half of the leg pole! This is just what England needed to start this session. A really, really good knock by Sharma ends. He would have wanted to carry on to score a big one. He whacks the ground in anger and walks back to the hut.

... Day 3, Session 3 ...

England were quite good with the ball. Anderson, Overton and Robinson bowled in the right channels and went past the outside edge on numerous occasions. Curran struggled to find his rhythm and would want to change that. The key for England is to stay patient as a couple of quick wickets will help them push further for a victory. Do join us at 4 pm Local (3 pm GMT) for the last session on Day 3.

The session was all about Rohit Sharma and Cheteshwar Pujara. Both the batters have put their heads down and have indulged in some good old-fashioned Test-match batting. They have blocked the balls which deserved to be blocked, punished the balls that deserved the treatment and left the ones which were too wide. Rohit Sharma has looked very solid so far and Pujara has surprisingly scored runs at a brisk pace. India would hope that these two can cut down the deficit even further.

A wonderful, wonderful session for India. Rohit Sharma and Cheteshwar Pujara have batted and batted to take them to 112. The deficit is now 242 and they would be quite happy going in the hut. England were pretty good with the ball too, but could not take a single wicket.

Right then. We have a massive session coming up. The English pacers are breathing fire and the Indian middle order has not been in the best of form. The next session could very well decide which way this game goes. Do join us at 1:40 pm local (12:40 pm GMT) for the second session!

India started quite well on Day 3 and picked up two wickets early. But what followed was a wonderful display of fast bowling by England. James Anderson, Ollie Robinson, Craig Overton and Sam Curran bowled the right channels and got plenty of help from the overcast conditions and the pitch. The English pacers troubled both Rohit Sharma and KL Rahul and went past the edge on many occasions. It looked like India would go back for Lunch without losing a wicket but the wicket of KL Rahul on the last ball of the session will make them a bit more nervous in the break.

What a session of Test cricket! The wicket of Rahul just before Lunch has provided England with a really good start in this innings. Rohit Sharma has looked quite solid and would need to continue if India are to get back in the game.

OUT! EDGED AND CAUGHT! What a catch this is by Bairstow. Wonderful delivery too from Overton and just at the stroke of Lunch, KL Rahul's innings has been cut short. Outstanding piece of cricket from England and they will head back as the happier side. Overton serves this on a length, around the off pole, KL Rahul is forced to play at this due to the angle, but the ball nips away enough to catch the outside edge. The ball goes in between Joe Root (first slip) and Jonny Bairstow (second slip) and Bairstow dives to his left and takes a one-handed stunner. Jubilation for England here. THAT WILL BE LUNCH ON DAY 3!

Slightly behind the good length, lands outside off and comes back in nicely. Rohit Sharma looks to work this to the leg side, but misses to get hit on the pad. No ball called as Ollie Robinson has overstepped.
Way outside off, left alone.
On a length, angling in around off, Rahul strides forward and middles his push towards point for one.
On a length, just outside off. Sharma decides to leave it at the last moment. The ball hits the bat and goes towards the slip cordon.
Length ball, on leg. Sharma works it past mid-wicket for a couple of runs.
Fuller ball, outside off. Left alone now.
Short of third slip! Length ball, on off. Sharma looks to block but gets the edge. But since he is playing with soft hands, the ball lands short of the diving third slip fielder.
Full ball, on leg. Blocked out by Sharma.
Back of a length, around off. Sharma blocks it out. He wants the single but is sent back by Rahul.
Beaten again! On a length, lands outside off and comes back in. Rahul looks to block but the ball zips past the outside edge.
On a length, wide enough to be left alone.
Full again, just outside off. Rahul gets the edge while looking to block. The ball goes towards gully.

This comes back in! Full ball, lands on off and comes back in. Rahul looks to work it away but gets hit on the pads. There is an appeal for LBW but turned down. Root suggests that there was some bat on it and the replay confirms the same.
Full ball, on off. Rahul looks to block but gets no bat on it.
Length ball, on leg. Rahul works it to square leg.
Full ball, wide enough to be left alone.
Length ball, on off. Worked to the leg side.

Beaten again! Length ball, on off. Sharma looks to block it from the crease but the ball goes past the edge. There is a noise as the ball goes past the bat and an appeal is put in for caught behind. It is turned down and Craig Overton says that it hit the pads. The replay confirms the same.
Fuller ball, on leg. Worked to the leg side.
And again! Length ball, on off. Sharma looks to block and the ball goes past the edge. Jos Buttler collects it over his head.
Beaten! Length ball, just outside off. Sharma hangs his bat out but the ball goes past the edge.
On a length, wide outside off. Rahul has no intentions of offering a stroke to this one.
Full ball, just outside off. Rahul blocks it out.
Length ball, but wide enough for Rahul to let the keeper collect it.
Fuller ball, on off. Blocked out.

Full ball, on leg. Rahul looks to block it but gets hit on the pads. The ball lobs up and is taken by Haseeb Hameed at short leg. The fielders put in a big appeal for a catch but it is turned down. They do not take the review too.
Full ball, on off. Sharma whips it to deep square leg for one.
Fuller ball, lands on the fifth stump. Left alone by Rahul.
Length ball, just outside off. Rahul gets forward but keeps it bat behind the pads to leave it alone.
Back of a length, a lot closer to the off pole. But wide enough for Rahul to leave it without any fuss.
Outswinger but starts way outside off. Rahul leaves this one.
Full ball, way outside off. Left alone.
Full ball, on leg. Sharma works it past square leg for one.
Length outside off, Rahul looks to defend but the ball whistles past the edge to the keeper.
On off, defended.
Review time! KL Rahul reviews this with a second left on the clock. No bat on that one. The ball is going down leg! KL Rahul is safe!

NOT OUT! The review works out for India and Rahul as the on-field decision has been overturned. Robinson hurls across a length delivery, around the off pole, the ball hits the deck and nips back in sharply on this occasion. Rahul looks to defend this one but the ball misses his willow and goes onto ping his pad. An appeal and the finger goes up this time. Rahul has a word with Rohit and with just one single second left on the timer, Rahul opts for the same. Ball Tracker shows that the ball was missing the stumps. Good decision by KL Rahul!
One more run as Rohit Sharma exploits the same area that KL did on the previous ball. India behind by 338 runs.
A single as this was nudged in between mid-wicket and square leg.
Hurls a good length ball around off, KL Rahul presses forward and blocks it out solidly.
Length on off, defended to square leg.
Fourth stump line again, on a length, Sharma leaves it untouched.
The batsman has just blocked that from his crease.
In the fourth-stump channel, outside off, the ball seams away as Rohit prods forward and makes a leave.
Left alone as this was bowled outside off.
Around off, Rohit taps this to point.
Outside off, short of a length, Rahul keeps a close eye on this and shoulders arms this time.
Length, lands outside off, nips back sharply and hits him Rahul on the thigh pad.
Anderson slants a length ball on the body, this is nudged out to the mid on region. 'NO RUN, NO RUN!' quips Rahul.
Similar line and length as the previous ball, Rahul, this time, gets bat on ball as he taps this to the leg side.
Short of a length, angling in, Rahul looks to work this to the leg side but misses and gets hit high on the pad.
Angled into the pads, Sharma nurdles this to deep square leg and rotates the strike.
Closer to the off pole on a length, KL comes ahead, sniffs at the ball, and makes a late decision to let the ball be.
Good length on off, Rahul blocks this solidly.
Outside off, KL holds himself back and makes a leave.
Around off, defended out.
Short of a length, around off, RS goes back and nudges this to the leg side for a run.
FOUR! Sweetly timed by Rohit Sharma. On a length, outside off, swings away and Rohit Sharma leans ahead and creams this through covers for a boundary.
On off, KL gets ahead to defend but misses and gets hit on the pad.
Fuller, outside off, left alone.
On the pads, clipped through mid-wicket for a couple of runs.

Length delivery, around off, KL Rahul prods ahead and looks to block but misses and gets hit on the pad. An appeal but turned down. The height seemed to be an issue. Replays show that the impact was outside off too.
An action replay of the previous delivery.
Outside off on a length, KL Rahul shoulders arms.
Full ball, on off. Sharma pushes it back to the bowler.
Full ball, on off. Blocked out.
Back of a length, but quite wide outside off. Left alone yet again by Sharma.
Length ball, just outside off. Sharma trusts the bounce and leaves this one.
Full ball, on leg. Rahul works it past square leg for one.
Here comes the inswinger! Length ball, lands on off and nips back in. Rahul looks to work it away but gets hit high on the pads.
A touch fuller, but wide enough for Sharma to leave it without any fuss.
Back of a length, just outside off. Sharma leaves it.
On a length, outside off. Sharma leaves this one.
Back of a length, on off. Blocked out.
Back of a length, just outside off. Sharma leaves this one.
Length ball, on leg. Rahul works it to fine leg for one.
Length ball, outside off. Sharma leaves this one with ease.
Just short again! Length ball, on off. Sharma looks to block but gets the edge again. The ball lands short of the slips yet again.
Fuller ball, on off. Sharma gets the edge but it falls short of the slip cordon.
Length ball, outside off. Left alone.
Beaten! This lands on off so Rohit Sharma is forced to play at it. The ball moves away sharply and goes past the outside edge.
Outswinger, this starts outside off and nips away. Sharma leaves it alone.
Back of a length, wide enough for Rahul to leave it with ease.
Length ball, on middle. Sharma gets the inside edge to the leg side for a single.
On a length, outside off. Sharma covers the stumps and then leaves it.
Back of a length, outside off. Left alone.
KL Rahul is off the mark! Length ball, on off. He strides forward and pushes it past cover for one.
Full ball, outside off. Rahul leaves this one alone.
Ollie Robinson to start from the other end.

Length ball, outside off. Sharma gets the outside edge while looking to defend. The ball goes past gully. Haseeb Hameed chases it and dives to pull it back in. Jonny Bairstow throws the ball back in and two runs are taken. India are underway.
Full ball, way outside off. Sharma has no interest in offering a stroke.
Fuller ball, on off. Sharma prods forward and taps it to the off side.
Well bowled! Length ball, just outside off. Sharma looks to defend but pulls his bat out at the last moment.
Back of a length, around off. Sharma blocks it from the crease.
A nice outswinger, it lands outside off. Sharma prods forward and leaves it.
